(50170,	4,	'3837-1463513100-1463520600@www.cambridgesustainablefood.org',	'What IS the deal with meat? Cambridge Carbon Footprint @ Eat festival',	'Thereâ€™s been a lot of media attention around the impact of meat on our health and the environment. What are the facts? Cambridge Carbon Footprint invites festival goers to â€˜What IS the deal with meat?â€™, a hot topic panel discussion and Q&A. <br/>Speakers, including leading figures on food sustainability Tara Garnett (founder of the Food Climate Research Network) and Clare Oxborrow (Head of the Land, Food and Water Team at FOE) will discuss the health, welfare and environmental issues related to the our ever increasing consumption of meat. The other two panellists are Angelika von Heimendahl of CamCattle, whose cattle are seen roaming the Cambridge commons, and Carine Henry, paediatric dietician, who is a member of our CSF committee. What are the facts about our rising meat consumption? Are there solutions out there? What technologies, policies and behaviour change might help? Join us in the beautiful setting of â€˜The Divinity Schoolâ€™ at St Johnâ€™s to find out more. Find out more here. <br/> <br/>Free event, no booking required. Get there early to secure a seat! The event will start on time as Tara has to leave at 9. <br/>',	'2016-05-17 19:25:00',	'2016-05-17 21:30:00',	'http://www.cambridgesustainablefood.org/event/what-is-the-deal-with-meat-cambridge-carbon-footprint-eat-festival/',	'All Saints Passage, St. John\'s Street, Cambridge, United Kingdom',	'2016-04-22 05:34:18',	'',	'',	'http://www.cambridgesustainablefood.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/eat-cambridge-2016.png'),
