(55202,	6,	'13184-1464442200-1464456600@centreforglobalequality.org',	'Field Ready Make-a-thon',	'Are you interested in engineering, technology, science, making or humanitarian aid in general? Do you enjoy problem solving and making? Can you spare a few hours on a Saturday afternoon to help solve a real world development problem? <br/> <br/>One of the Centre for Global Equality\'s member organisations, Field Ready, is a start-up NGO focused on solving humanitarian supply chain problems through innovative manufacturing approaches. Aid agencies spend 60-80% of their income on procurement and logistics, yet in post-disaster responses, those in the field experience severe problems. In remote, difficult to access locations, finding unique parts â€“ replacement parts to a medical device, pieces of a vehicle or generator, custom-made rehabilitation items such as a prosthetic limb â€“ is a vital function for basic operations. However, these items are normally only available in major cities, or even only from an international supplier. The transport costs are often unjustifiable for unique or low volume components. Field Ready are seeking to solve these problems through local manufacture. In particular, we have a focus on additive manufacturing. <br/> <br/>The Make-a-thon is an event of intense brainstorming and prototyping aimed at solving a particular technical challenge. The process generally includes coming up with theoretical solutions, taking a few of them forwards to proof of concept prototyping, presenting the findings and hopefully one or more of these will serve as a basis for future development. <br/> <br/>The theme of this Makers Hackathon will be construction quality in Haiti. Specifically, generating solutions to how concrete blocks can be quality tested on the site of delivery to ensure safe construction. <br/> <br/>Where: Institute for Manufacturing, 17 Charles Babbage Road, Cambridge, CB3 0FS <br/>When: 28 May 2016 from 1.30pm - 5.30pm <br/> <br/>Please visit the website for more information and to buy tickets.',	'2016-05-28 13:30:00',	'2016-05-28 17:30:00',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/event/field-ready-make-thon/',	'17 Charles Babbage Road, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, CB3 0FS, United Kingdom',	'2016-05-18 14:35:20',	'',	'',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Field-Ready.png'),
(55203,	6,	'13180-1465324200-1465335000@centreforglobalequality.org',	'Development i-Teams Final Presentations',	'i-Teams combines multi-disciplinary teams of students with industry mentors and real University inventions to assess the commercial viability of new technologies and product designs. <br/> <br/>Students gain real hands-on experience of investigating potential markets for a new technology, while researchers are given early feedback from potential partners and customers. <br/> <br/>Teams of up to 7 students, selected from across all disciplines, work for a term (2 weeks for Taster projects) with the support of their team mentor, their researchers and the i-Teams Programme Director. <br/> <br/>This event will see the final presentations for the Development i-Teams programme presented. This term\'s projects are: <br/>Diagnosing anaemia at point-of-care, with Tanya Hutter, Chemistry <br/>Investigating the impact of blood transfusion services in the developing world, with Krishnaa Mahbubani, Chemical Engineering & Biotechnology <br/>Improving the storage of biogas, with Andrew Marsden & David Fairen-Jiminez, Chemical Engineering & Biotechnology, Immaterial Labs <br/>Where: Institute for Manufacturing, 17 Charles Babbage Road, Cambridge, CB3 0FS <br/>When: 7th June, 6.30pm - 9.30pm <br/> <br/>For more information, please visit the website. Food is provided, but please register at the Eventbrite page.',	'2016-06-07 18:30:00',	'2016-06-07 21:30:00',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/event/development-i-teams-final-presentations-2/',	'17 Charles Babbage Road, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, CB3 0FS, United Kingdom',	'2016-05-18 14:37:52',	'',	'',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/iteams_header-300x86.png'),
(55204,	6,	'13181-1465372800-1466010000@centreforglobalequality.org',	'Open Technology Week Cambridge',	'Open Technology Week will take place across the city between 8-15 June 2016, culminating in a gathering and open source Maker Faire at the Cambridge University Engineering Department on 15 June. <br/> <br/>Open technologies are increasingly prevalent in society. From cell phone operating systems to high performance computing, open source software provides some of the most powerful tools to tackle today\'s challenges. The Open Technology Week will showcase and celebrate open and open source technologies developed across Cambridge and beyond. We\'ll be asking why open matters, who benefits and in what contexts does greater openness make sense across a diverse array of established and emerging areas from synthetic biology to additive manufacturing to big data analytics. Independently organised events (lectures, workshop, demos, hackathons, maker evenings etc.) will take place across the city between 8-15 June 2016, culminating in a one-day gathering with talks and open source maker faire at the Cambridge University Engineering Department on 15 June. <br/> <br/>For more information and a list of all the events taking place, please visit the website. <br/> <br/>Where:  Various locations in Cambridge <br/>When:  8th to 15th June <br/> <br/> ',	'2016-06-08 08:00:00',	'2016-06-15 17:00:00',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/event/open-technology-week-cambridge/',	'Cambridge, Cambridgeshire',	'2016-05-18 14:36:46',	'',	'',	''),
(55205,	6,	'13183-1465459200-1466010000@centreforglobalequality.org',	'The Open Technology for Development Make-a-thon ',	'  <br/> <br/>As part of Open Technology Week, The Centre for Global Equality is setting the challenges for the Open Technology for Development Make-a-thon, which brings hardware design challenges from international development and humanitarian contexts to problem-solvers. They are then challenged over the course of five days to prototype solutions using open source technologies. Up to twelve challenges for technology solutions to problems in international development and humanitarian contexts will be put forward by the Centre for Global Equality. All challenges will potentially be surmountable with the kit and equipment provided and some creativity! More than one team is welcome to work on each challenge. <br/> <br/>Support and funding will be awarded for the most promising prototype and all participants are invited to stay involved with progressing the resulting project. <br/> <br/>On the 9th June, participants will be introduced to the challenges, the kit and the fully equipped Dyson workshops at Cambridge University Engineering Department. They will then have a few days to form teams, think and design before a two-day making sprint in the workshops on the 13th and 14th June, as well as a chance to get feedback on your prototypes at the Open Technology Maker Faire on 15th June. <br/>If this sounds interesting please apply to join! Places are limited to 50 and the deadline for applications is 20 May 2016. <br/> <br/>  <br/> <br/>Dates:  9-15 June 2016 (9, 13, 14 and 15 have scheduled activities) <br/>Venue:  Dyson Building at Cambridge University Engineering Department <br/>Contact:  Jenny Molloy (<a href=\"mailto:jcm80@cam.ac.uk\">jcm80@cam.ac.uk</a>) for any queries. <br/>Please visit the website to apply. This event open to Undergraduates at the University of Cambridge from any subject.',	'2016-06-09 08:00:00',	'2016-06-15 17:00:00',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/event/open-technology-development-make-thon/',	'Trumpington Street, Cambridge, Cambridge, CB2 1PZ, United Kingdom',	'2016-05-18 14:36:28',	'',	'',	''),
(55206,	6,	'13191-1465500600-1465507800@centreforglobalequality.org',	'Ditch Coal Roadshow',	'Four coal fired power stations have closed in the last six months. The coal industry is choking on its own fumes, but we need to help it into its death throes. <br/> <br/>Hosted by the Cambridge Zero Carbon Society and the Coal Action Network, the main speaker is Vladimir Slivyak from Ecodefense, a radical Russian group raising awareness of the plight of indigenous Shor and Teleut people living in the Russian coalfields that supply coal to the UK. The Ditch Coal Roadshow will follow coal from the point of extraction - focussing on mines in the UK and Russia - to their coal fired power stations. <br/> <br/>The Coal Action Network\'s own speaker will talk about the situation in the UK\'s opencast coal mines and power stations, and will lead discussion with audience members about what can be done about the state of the industry. <br/> <br/>Where:  The Lecture Theatre, Trinity Hall College, Trinity Lane, Cambridge, CB2 1TJ <br/>When: 9th June, 19:30â€“21:30 <br/> <br/>Please visit the Facebook page for this event for more information.',	'2016-06-09 19:30:00',	'2016-06-09 21:30:00',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/event/ditch-coal-roadshow/',	'Trinity College, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire',	'2016-05-18 14:33:38',	'',	'',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Ditch-Coal.png'),
(55207,	6,	'13178-1465551000-1465579800@centreforglobalequality.org',	'Technology for the Bottom Billion Workshop',	'Hosted by CRASSH <br/> <br/>Cambridge is a global leader in science and technology, and advances pioneered in Cambridge have impacted significantly on the lives of the worldâ€™s poorest and most marginalised people. To date, however, this impact has not been uniformly positive. Most of the benefits of cutting edge science are enjoyed by the worldâ€™s wealthiest 10%, while the bottom 50% bear the brunt of the externalities that new technologies so often generate. <br/> <br/>This workshop brings together people who are working to change this situation by evolving innovative technological responses to challenges faced by people who live on less than $2 per day. <br/> <br/>Presentations will be made by University of Cambridge academics and students, practitioners from NGOs and civil society organisations, social entrepreneurs running their own ventures and entrepreneurs working on social innovation initiatives in large corporations. <br/> <br/>Join us for an exciting day of presentations from NGOs, social enterprises and academics. <br/>Attendance is free and lunch will be provided, but please do register as places are limited and will be allocated on first come, first served basis. <br/> <br/>Where: Seminar Room SG1, Ground Floor, Alison Richard Building, CB3 9DT <br/>When: 10th June, 9.30am - 5.30pm <br/> <br/>For more information, please visit the website, or register here. <br/> <br/>Call for Contributions <br/> <br/>If you are involved in an initiative that uses technology to enhance the lives of people who live on less than $2 per day, and would like to discuss your work with like-minded people, please send an email with the information below to lara.allen@centreforglobalequality by the 25th of June. <br/> <br/>Workshop Contribution Submission Information <br/> <br/>Name <br/> <br/>Department, Organisation or Company <br/> <br/>Title of Presentation/Poster <br/> <br/>Short Summary (less than 200 words) <br/> <br/>Type of presentation: Spoken presentation (20 minutes), 5 minute pitch, Poster',	'2016-06-10 09:30:00',	'2016-06-10 17:30:00',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/event/technology-bottom-billion-workshop/',	'Alison Richard Building, 7 West Road, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, CB3 9DT',	'2016-05-18 14:41:27',	'',	'',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Bottom-Billion.png'),
(55209,	6,	'13185-1466496000-1466874000@centreforglobalequality.org',	'Synbio Hackathon',	'In collaboration with the University of Cambridge Department of Plant Sciences, Cambridge University Technology and Enterprise Club (CUTEC) is proud to organise the UK\'s first synthetic biology themed hackathon event. <br/> <br/>This event puts together diverse teams of people to solve a unique biological problem. Participants spend four days in synthetic biology lab with access to hardware, software and bioware prototyping tools and then pitch their solution at the annual Technology Ventures Conference. Judges from industry decide on the most novel solutions and the winning team gets £1500. The most commercial solution will be offered help to take it to the next stage including a place on the Accelerate-Cambridge program hosted by the Judge Business School. <br/> <br/>Entry: The cost of the competition is £400 which covers accommodation for 5 nights and attendance at the Technology Ventures Conference. Meals are not included. Scholarships are available to cover travel and accommodation and those without funding are encouraged to apply. <br/> <br/>Where: Department of Plant Sciences, University of Cambridge, CB2 3EA <br/>When: 21st - 25th June 2016 <br/> <br/>Deadline for applications: 30th May <br/>For more information and to apply, please visit the website.',	'2016-06-21 08:00:00',	'2016-06-25 17:00:00',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/event/synbio-hackathon/',	'University of Cambridge , Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, CB2 3EA, United Kingdom',	'2016-05-18 14:34:48',	'',	'',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Bio-Hackathon-Screenshot.png'),
(55210,	6,	'13195-1466668800-1466787600@centreforglobalequality.org',	'Cambridge Conference on Global Food Security',	'The Cambridge Conference on Global Food Security is hosted by the University of Cambridge Global Food Security Initiative in association with the Cambridge Conservation Initiative & the Cambridge Centre of Development Studies. <br/> <br/>The Conference will explore how to translate knowledge into action to secure future food supply, sustainability and equality. It aims to cover the most exciting developments, and identify the most pressing knowledge gaps, across a wide range of different fields, seeking bridges across some of the fault-lines in Global Food Security discourse: small-holder farming versus agri-business, natural versus social science perspectives, grassroots versus top-down solutions, food security versus sovereignty, global supply chains versus local markets, global governance versus consumer power. <br/> <br/>  <br/> <br/>Where: David Attenborough Building, Pembroke St, Cambridge, CB2 3QY <br/>When: 23-24 June 2016 <br/>Price: £39 (standard) and £19.50 (students) for the Thursday and Friday programmes, with reduced prices for either day. <br/> <br/>For more information and to book your place, please visit the website, or book tickets here.',	'2016-06-23 08:00:00',	'2016-06-24 17:00:00',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/event/cambridge-conference-global-food-security/',	'Pembroke Street, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, CB2 3QY, United Kingdom',	'2016-05-18 14:34:16',	'',	'',	'http://centreforglobalequality.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Global-food-security.png'),
